ll, Yorkshire, England":"Grindale, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"–":"Overleden","1342–Male":"1342–Overleden","1370–1402":"1370–1402","–Female":"Overleden","1402":"1402","1342":"1342","1370":"1370","about 1760":"circa 1760","Grindall, Yorkshire, England":"Grindale, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","1342–Male":"1342–Deceased","1370–1402":"1370–1402","–Female":"Deceased","1402":"1402","1342":"1342","1370":"1370","about 1760":"about 1760","Grindall, Yorkshire, England":"Grindale, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Somerville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Graveron-Sémerville in Eure (Normandy), from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sigimar</i> (see   Siemer  ) + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. The surname was taken to Scotland in the 12th century by William <i>de Somerville</i>, a retainer of David, Earl of Huntingdon, who became King David I of Scotland.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Somacháin</b> (see   Summers  ) or <b>Mag Shamradháin</b> (see   Somers  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Siemer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Helmuth, Otto, Theresia.","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Siegmar</i>, composed of the elements <i>sigi</i> ‘victory’ + <i>mari</i>, <i>meri</i> ‘famous’."]},{"name":"Sommerville","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire): variant of   Somerville   1."]},{"name":"Summerville","meanings":["English, Scottish (Lanarkshire), and Irish: variant of   Somerville  . This form of the surname is particularly common in Ireland."]},{"name":"Simrell","meanings":["Scottish: perhaps related to the Ulster name<b>Sumeril</b>, a variant of   Somerville  ."]},{"name":"Summerfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>sumor</i> ‘summer’ + <i>feld</i> ‘field, open land’, denoting summer pasture or fields cultivated only in summer, such as Summerfield in Woodnesborough (Kent), Somerfield Court in Sellindge (Kent), and Summerfield in Marlborough (Wiltshire).","English: variant of   Somerville  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Sommerfeld  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Roger Somerville married Roger Somerville about 1760. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1342–Male":"1342–Surnud","1370–1402":"1370–1402","–Female":"Surnud","1402":"1402","1342":"1342","1370":"1370","about 1760":"umbes 1760","Grindall, Yorkshire, England":"Grindale, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1342–Male":"1342–Kuollut","1370–1402":"1370–1402","–Female":"Kuollut","1402":"1402","1342":"1342","1370":"1370","about 1760":"noin 1760","Grindall, Yorkshire, England":"Grindale, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1342–Male":"1342–Décédé","1370–1402":"1370–1402","–Female"